{
  "query": "What are the benefits and harms of using acoustic devices on fishing gear in coastal waters to protect porpoises?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on 33 studies primarily conducted in coastal waters, using acoustic devices on fishing gear provides significant benefits for porpoise conservation. The most substantial benefit is the reduction in porpoise entanglements, with nine controlled studies finding fewer entanglements of harbour porpoises when acoustic devices were used on cod traps or fishing nets in the North Atlantic Ocean, North Sea, South Atlantic Ocean, North Pacific Ocean, Black Sea, and South Pacific Ocean (Action ID: 2808). However, three studies found mixed results where acoustic devices reduced entanglements of some species but not others.\n\nBehavioural evidence shows that harbour porpoises and other marine mammals generally respond to acoustic deterrents by maintaining greater distances from fishing gear. Twelve of sixteen controlled studies found that harbour porpoises, common bottlenose dolphins, tuxuci dolphins, finless porpoises and seals approached nets less closely, had fewer encounters with nets, or reduced their activity in surrounding areas when acoustic devices were deployed (Action ID: 2808).\n\nPotential harms identified include habitat exclusion effects, where one controlled study in the Bay of Fundy found that while acoustic devices on moorings initially reduced harbour porpoise echolocation activity, porpoises actually increased their probability of approaching within 125m of the device over 10-11 days, suggesting potential habituation (Action ID: 2816). Additionally, two studies found that acoustic devices on vessels did not reduce predation by Risso's dolphins on squid catches and had limited effects on dolphin behaviour (Action ID: 2815).\n\nThe evidence indicates that while acoustic devices are generally effective at reducing porpoise bycatch and entanglements, their effectiveness can vary by location, species, and potentially decrease over time due to habituation.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2808",
    "2816",
    "2815",
    "2807"
  ]
}

